    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-01-09T08:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-01-09T08:00:00-05:00" n="22"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d22">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/3469: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain (<persName corresp="#p_AR1"
                            type="from">Atherton</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-01-09T13:00:00+00:00"
                            >January 9, 1932—1 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received January 9—9:50 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>7. Foreign Office has at noon today handed the following communiqué to press
                    correspondents: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“His Majesty’s Government stand by the policy of the open door for
                            international trade in Manchuria which is guaranteed by the Nine-Power
                            Treaty of Washington. Since recent events in Manchuria the Japanese
                            representative on the Council of the League of Nations stated on October
                                13th<note n="17" xml:id="d22fn17">For brief report of this
                                statement, see telegram No. 196, October 14, 1931, 9 a.m., from the
                                Consul at Geneva, <ref target="frus1931v03#pg_189">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1931, vol. <hi
                                        rend="smallcaps">iii</hi>, p. 189</ref>.</note> that Japan
                            was the champion in Manchuria of the principle of equal opportunity and
                            of the open door for the economic activities of all nations. Further, on
                            December 28th the Japanese Prime Minister stated<note n="18"
                                xml:id="d22fn18">See <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> of January
                                11 from the British Embassy, <ref target="#pg_22">p.
                                22</ref>.</note> that Japan would adhere to the open-door policy and
                            would welcome foreign participation and cooperation in Manchurian
                            enterprises. In view of these statements His Majesty’s Government does
                            not consider it necessary to address any formal note to the Japanese
                            Government on the lines of the American Government’s note, but the
                            Japanese Ambassador has been requested to obtain confirmation of these
                            assurances from his Government.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_AR1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Atherton</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
